The Scenario: A company states the average (mean) salary is $22,000, suggesting decent pay. Employees claim they struggle, with many earning only $12,000
The Analysis:
Mean (Average): High salaries of 1-2 executives increase this value, creating a misleading representation of typical income.
Median (Middle): Arranging all salaries from lowest to highest and picking the middle value provides a better picture of the "middle" employee.
Mode (Common): The most frequently occurring salary (e.g., $12,000) highlights what the largest group of workers actually earns.
Conclusion: The union should use the median or mode to highlight that most workers are below the company-cited mean salary
